message_1:
Find the inverse of the matrix A =  
\begin{bmatrix}
2 & 4 \\
-1 & 3 \\
\end{bmatrix}

message_2:
To find the inverse of a 2x2 matrix A, we can use the following formula:

A^(-1) = (1/det(A)) * adj(A)

where det(A) is the determinant of A and adj(A) is the adjugate of A.

First, let's find the determinant of A:

det(A) = (2 * 3) - (4 * -1) = 6 + 4 = 10

Now, let's find the adjugate of A:

adj(A) = \begin{bmatrix}
3 & -4 \\
1 & 2 \\
\end{bmatrix}

Now, we can find the inverse of A:

A^(-1) = (1/10) * \begin{bmatrix}
3 & -4 \\
1 & 2 \\
\end{bmatrix}

A^(-1) = \begin{bmatrix}
0.3 & -0.4 \\
0.1 & 0.2 \\
\end{bmatrix}

So, the inverse of the matrix A is:

\begin{bmatrix}
0.3 & -0.4 \\
0.1 & 0.2 \\
\end{bmatrix}
